  1. 3
    Getting Started [70 ms]

    Features 3 0 0
    Scenarios 4 0 0

    1. 1
      Installing The Framework [0 ms]

      Scenarios 1 0 0 
      As a developer
You can leverage xBDD within your .Net testing projects
By installing the xBDD.Core nuget package

      1. 3 Via A Nuget Package [0 ms]

        1. Given you have created a test project [0 ms]
        2. When you excute the following command in the project directory: [Input] [0 ms] 
          dotnet add package xBDD
        3. Then you will install the xBDD framework [0 ms]

    2. 2
      Executing Your First Scenario [60 ms]

      Scenarios 2 0 0 
      As a developer
You can automate a basic scenario
By using xB.AddScenario and the Given, When, Then, and And operations.

      1. 3 That Passes [30 ms]

        1. Given you have a similar class in your test project that defines your first scenario: [Output] [1 ms] 
          namespace MySample.Features.MyFirstArea
{
	using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
    using System;
	using System.Threading.Tasks;
	using xBDD;

    [TestClass]
    [AsA("sample user")]
    [YouCan("have my first feature value")]
    [By("execute my first feature")]
    public class MyFirstFeature: FeatureTestClass
    {

        [TestMethod]
        public async Task MyFirstScenario()
        {
            await xB.CurrentRun.AddScenario(this, 1)
                 .Given("my step 1", (s) => { 
                    //Add code to perform action.
                 })
                .When("my step 2", (s) => { 
                    //Add code to perform action.
                 })
                .Then("my step 3", (s) => { 
                    //Add code to perform action.
                 })
               .Run();
        }
    }
}
        2. When you execute the tests in the test project [0 ms]
        3. Then you will see the output matches this template (See TemplateValidator project on Nuget): [Input] [12 ms] 
          My Sample Features

My Sample - Features - My First Area
	My First Feature
		My First Scenario
			Given my step 1
			When my step 2
			Then my step 3

      2. 3 That Failed [5 ms]

        1. Given you have a similar class in your test project that defines your first failing scenario: [Output] [0 ms] 
          namespace MySample.Features.MyFirstArea
{
	using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
    using System;
	using System.Threading.Tasks;
	using xBDD;

    [TestClass]
    [AsA("sample user")]
    [YouCan("have my first failing feature value")]
    [By("execute my first failing feature")]
    public class MyFirstFailingFeature: FeatureTestClass
    {

        [TestMethod]
        public async Task MyFirstScenario()
        {
            await xB.CurrentRun.AddScenario(this, 1)
                 .Given("my step 1", (s) => { 
                    //Add code to perform action.
                 })
                .When("my step 2", (s) => { 
                    //Add code to perform action.
                    throw new Exception("My first exception.");
                 })
                .Then("my step 3", (s) => { 
                    //Add code to perform action.
                 })
               .Run();
        }
    }
}

    3. 1
      Leveraging Reusable Steps [6 ms]

      Scenarios 1 0 0 
      As a developer
You can simplify the development of tests
By using a library of reusable steps

      1. 4 By Using An Actor Class [6 ms]

        1. Given you have a similar class in your test project for defining reusable steps: [Output] [0 ms] 
          namespace MySample.Actors
{
    using xBDD;
    using xBDD.Model;
    public class MyActor 
    {
        public const string Name = "My Actor";
        public Step ExcuteFirstAction()
        {
            return xB.CreateStep("you execute a first action", (step) => {});
        }
        public Step ExcuteAnotherAction()
        {
            return xB.CreateStep("you execute another action", (step) => {});
        }
        public Step WillSeeAResult()
        {
            return xB.CreateStep("you will see a result", (step) => {});
        }
    }
}
        2. And you have a similar class in your test project that defines a feature using the reusable steps: [Output] [0 ms] 
          namespace MySample.Features.MyArea_1
{
	using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
    using System;
	using System.Threading.Tasks;
	using xBDD;
    using MySample.Actors;

    [TestClass]
    [AsA(MyActor.Name)]
    [YouCan("have my feature 1 value")]
    [By("execute my feature 1")]
    public class MyFeature_ReusableSteps: FeatureTestClass
    {
        MyActor you = new MyActor();

        [TestMethod]
        public async Task MyScenario_WithReusableSteps()
        {
            await xB.CurrentRun.AddScenario(this, 1)
                .Given(you.ExcuteFirstAction())
                .When(you.ExcuteAnotherAction())
                .Then(you.WillSeeAResult())
                .Run();
        }
    }
}
        3. When you execute the tests in the test project [0 ms]
        4. Then you will see the output matches this template (See TemplateValidator project on Nuget): [Input] [5 ms] 
          My Sample Features

My Sample - Features - My Area 1
{{.*}}/rl
	My Feature Reusable Steps
		My Scenario With Reusable Steps
			Given you execute a first action
			When you execute another action
			Then you will see a result

    Generate Reports - Customize Html Report [8,308 ms]

    Features 2 0 1

    1. 3
      Write Failures Only [179 ms]

      Scenarios 3 0 0 
      As a Developer
You can set the html report to only report on failures
By passing the report writer a true value for the failuresOnly parameter.

      1. 3 Passing [70 ms]

        1. Given you generate an html report from test results of a single passing scenario set to report only failures [1 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [40 ms]
        3. Then you will see the test run areas list is not there [28 ms]

      2. 3 Skipped [30 ms]

        1. Given you generate an html report from test results of a single skipped scenario set to only report on failures [4 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single skipped scenario [17 ms]
        3. Then you will see the test run areas list is not there [8 ms]

      3. 3 Failing [74 ms]

        1. Given you generate an html report from test results of a full test run with all outcomes set to only report on failures [16 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a full test run with all outcomes [28 ms]
        3. Then you will see the step 2 with red badge is visible because the step failed and the report will be expanded to the failed step [29 ms]

    2. 3
      Shorten Area Name [1,234 ms]

      Scenarios 3 0 0 
      As a Developer
You can shorten the area name in the Html report.
By shorten the area name by removing the beginning of the name that matches a provided string

      1. 4 Matches Start Of Area Name [945 ms]

        1. Given you generate an html report from test results of a single passing scenario set to skip the string 'My ' in the area name [6 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [746 ms]
        3. Then you will see the area title line is visible [84 ms]
        4. And you will see the area title line has text 'Area 1' [106 ms]

      2. 4 Matches None Of Area Name [173 ms]

        1. Given you generate an html report from test results of a single passing scenario set to skip the string 'No Match' in the area name [6 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [24 ms]
        3. Then you will see the area title line is visible [63 ms]
        4. And you will see the area title line has text 'My Area 1' [80 ms]

      3. 4 Matches All Of Area Name [110 ms]

        1. Given you generate an html report from test results of a single passing scenario set to skip the string 'My Area 1' in the area name [7 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [26 ms]
        3. Then you will see the area title line is visible [28 ms]
        4. And you will see the area title line has text '[Missing! (or Full Name Skipped)]' [47 ms]

    1. 1
      Generate Project Files From Test Run Results [2 ms]

      Scenarios 1 0 0 
      As a developer
You can generate a functioning test project from test run results
By calling the WriteAllCode method on the TestRun object.

      1. 5 Standard Full Report [2 ms]

        1. Given you have a test project that produces all outcomes [1 ms]
        2. And you have a similar class in your test project for setting up and breaking down the test run: [Output] [0 ms] 
          namespace MySample.Features
{
    using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
    using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting.Logging;
    using System;
    using System.IO;
    using System.Threading.Tasks;
    using xBDD;
    using xBDD.Browser;

    [TestClass]
    public class TestSetupAndBreakdown
    {

        [AssemblyInitialize]
        public static void TestRunStart(TestContext context)
        {
            xBDD.Browser.WebBrowser.WatchBrowser = TestConfiguration.WatchBrowswer;
        }
        [AssemblyCleanup()]
        public async static Task TestRunComplete()
        {
            WebDriver.Close();

            var directory = System.IO.Directory.GetCurrentDirectory();

            xB.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = TestConfiguration.TestRunName;

            System.IO.Directory.CreateDirectory($"{directory}/../../../test-results");

            xB.CurrentRun.SortTestRunResults(new FeatureSort().SortedFeatureNames);

            var htmlPath = directory + $"/../../../test-results/{TestConfiguration.HtmlReportFileName}";
            Logger.LogMessage("Writing Html Report to " + htmlPath);
            var htmlReport = await xB.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToHtml(TestConfiguration.RemoveFromAreaNameStart, TestConfiguration.FailuresOnly);
            File.WriteAllText(htmlPath, htmlReport);

            var textPath = directory + $"/../../../test-results/{TestConfiguration.TextReportFileName}";
            Logger.LogMessage("Writing Text Report to " + textPath);
            var textReport = await xB.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();
            File.WriteAllText(textPath, textReport);

            var jsonPath = directory + $"/../../../test-results/{TestConfiguration.JsonReportFileName}";
            Logger.LogMessage("Writing Json Report to " + jsonPath);
            var jsonReport = xB.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToJson();
            File.WriteAllText(jsonPath, jsonReport);

            var opmlPath = $"{directory}/../../../test-results/{TestConfiguration.OutlineReportFileName}";
            Logger.LogMessage("Writing OPML Report to " + opmlPath);
            var opmlReport = await xB.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToOpml();
            File.WriteAllText(opmlPath, opmlReport);

            await xB.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToCode("MySample.Features", "./Code/", "My Sample - Features - ");
        }
    }
}
        3. And you include this line of code: [Input] [0 ms] 
          xBDD.CurrentRun.WriteToCode("MySample.Features", "./Code/", "My Sample - Features - ")
        4. When you execute the tests in the test project [0 ms]
